1) What does it mean when a method returns a value in Java? Explain with an example.
-->When a method returns a value, it sends a result back to the caller using the return statement.

✅ Example
int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b; // returning value
}

public static void main(String[] args) {
    int result = add(10, 20);
    System.out.println(result); // 30
}

👉 Here, the method calculates and returns 30.



2) How is the return type of a method declared, and why must it match the returned value?
-->👉 The return type is declared before the method name.

    int add(int a, int b) // int is return type
    🔥 Why must it match?
    The value returned must be compatible with the declared type
    Otherwise → compile-time error
    ❌ Example (Error)
    int getValue() {
        return "Hello"; // ❌ String cannot be returned as int
    }



3) Can a method return different types of values based on conditions? Explain with example.
-->👉 Yes, but all returned values must be of the same type (or compatible)
    
    ✅ Example
    int check(int x) {
        if (x > 0)
            return 1;
        else
            return -1;
    }
    
    👉 Different values, but same type (int).



4) What happens if the return statement in a method is missing or mismatched with the declared return type?
-->❌ Case 1: Missing return
    int add(int a, int b) {
        // no return statement ❌
    }
    
    👉 Compile-time error
    
    ❌ Case 2: Mismatched return type
    int get() {
        return 10.5; // ❌ double to int
    }
    
    👉 Also compile-time error



5) What are covariant return types in Java, and how are they used in method overriding?
-->👉 If a method’s return type is a parent class, you can return an object of its subclass.
class Animal {}

class Dog extends Animal {}

class Test {
    Animal getAnimal() {
        return new Dog(); // returning subclass object
    }
}
